{{Infobox ethnic group | group = Turks in Poland | image = | caption = | population = 2,000–2,500<ref>{{cite web|author=Rep. of Turkey Ministry of Foreign Affairs|title=Turkey's Political Relations with Poland|url=http://www.mfa.gov.tr/turkey_s-political-relations-with-poland.en.mfa|accessdate=2009-10-24|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090731011632/http://www.mfa.gov.tr/turkey_s-political-relations-with-poland.en.mfa|archivedate=2009-07-31|df=}}</ref> | popplace = {{hlist|[[Warsaw]] | [[Poznań]] | [[Gdańsk]] | [[Łódź]]}} | langs = {{hlist|[[Turkish language|Turkish]] | [[Polish language|Polish]]}} | rels = [[Islam]] }} [[File:PolanTurkish.JPG|thumb|right|200px|A Turkish [[Kebab]] shop in [[Łódź]]]]
'''Turks in Poland''' are people of [[Turkish people|Turkish]] ethnicity living in [[Poland]] who form one of the country's smaller minority groups.
== Facts and figures ==
There is little coherent statistical data regarding the numbers of Turks residing in Poland. The majority of Turks live in Warsaw and Łódź but there are also Turkish communities in Gdańsk, Poznań, Krakow and Wroclaw and students in small cities like Lublin or Krosno.<ref>[https://www.academia.edu/7322801/Turkish_Community_in_Poland_from_Textile_Vendors_to_Top_Managers Pędziwiatr, K. (2014) Turkish Community in Poland: from Textile Vendors to Top Managers. In: Kujawa, K., eds Polish-Turkish Foreign Policy: 600 Years of Bilateral Relations”, Çanakkale University Publishing House]</ref>
== Turkish community == Many Turks in Poland are entrepreneurs and investors.<ref name="UnitedNations">{{Harvnb|United Nations Human Settlements Programme|2004|loc=95}}.</ref>
=== Demographics === The majority live in [[Warsaw]] or in the vicinity; but small communities of Turks are also reported in [[Poznań]], [[Gdańsk]] and [[Łódź]].<ref name="UnitedNations" />
